"Hulme M., Viner D.","A climate change scenario for the tropics",1998,"Climatic Change","39","2-3",,"145","176",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031875988&partnerID=40&md5=37ce5e94740d0dc7c7c9d84f7979e463","Climatic Research Unit, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom","Hulme, M., Climatic Research Unit, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; Viner, D., Climatic Research Unit, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom","This paper describes the construction of a climate change scenario for a region representing the 'extended' Tropics - 30°N to 30°S - using a methodology that combines results from a simple climate model and a Global Climate Model (GCM) transient climate change experiment. The estimated date by which this climate change scenario might be realized ranges from as early as the end of the 2030s to as late as well into the 22nd century. The central estimate is for this scenario to describe the climate of the 2060s, which would represent a global warming rate of about 0.2 °C per decade, with associated atmospheric CO2 concentrations estimated to be about 560 ppmv, 55% higher than 1990 levels. The role of anthropogenic aerosols in offsetting part of this future global warming and altering the regional character of the changes has not been considered. The paper presents changes in mean temperature; mean rainfall; rainfall seasonality, variability, frequency, and intensity and soil moisture. These patterns of change derive from only one GCM climate change experiment; different experiments would yield different patterns for the same global warming. There is also some discussion about possible changes in tropical cyclone (TC) activity, although since TCs remain poorly modelled in GCMs, the full range of possibilities (from reduced activity, through no change, to increased activity) should be considered in any impact assessment.",,"climate change; global warming",,,,,,"Alcamo, J., Bouwman, A., Edmonds, J., Grübler, A., Morita, T., Sugandhy, A., An Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios (1995) Climate Change 1994: Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and An Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emissions Scenarios, p. 339. , Houghton, J. T., Meira Filho, L. G., Bruce, J., Lee, H., Callander, B. A., Haites, E., Harris, N., and Maskell, K. (eds.), Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Barrow, E.M., Hulme, M., The Changing Probabilities of Daily Temperature Extremes in the UK Related to Future Global Warming and Changes in Climate Variability (1996) Clim. Res., 6, pp. 21-31; Bengtsson, L., Bottger, H., Kanamitsu, M., Simulation of Hurricane-Type Vortices in a General Circulation Model (1982) Tellus, 34, pp. 440-457; Broccoli, A.J., Manabe, S., Can Existing Climate Models be used to Study Anthropogenic Changes in Tropical Cyclone Climate? (1990) Geophys. Res. Lett., 17, pp. 1917-1920; Carnell, R.E., Senior, C.A., Mitchell, J.F.B., An Assessment of Measures of Storminess: Simulated Changes in Northern Hemisphere Winter Due to Increasing CO2 (1996) Clim. Dyn., 12, pp. 467-476; Carter, T.R., Parry, M.L., Nishioka, S., Harasawa, H., (1995) Technical Guidelines for Assessing Climate Change Impacts and Adaptations, p. 59. , University College London/Center for Global Environmental Research (Tsukuba), London/Tsukuba, Japan; Cubasch, U., Santer, B.D., Hellbach, A., Hegerl, G., Hock, H., Maier-Reimer, E., Mikolajewicz, U., Voss, R., Monte Carlo Climate Change Forecasts with a Global Coupled Ocean-Atmosphere Model (1994) Clim. Dyn., 10, pp. 1-20; Emmanuel, K.A., An Air-Sea Interaction Theory for Tropical Cyclones. I. Steady-State Maintenance (1986) J. Atmos. Sci., 43, pp. 585-604; Emmanuel, K.A., The Dependence of Hurricane Intensity on Climate (1987) Nature, 326, pp. 483-485; Emmanuel, K.A., The Intensity of Hurricanes (1988) J. Atmos. Sci., 45, pp. 1143-1155